Description: Typical range for pulsed fiber lasers at 1064 nm used in industrial cleaning of reflective metals like nickel; starting at 100 W balances efficiency and safety to avoid thermal damage due to nickel's high reflectivity (~60% at 1064 nm) and thermal conductivity (90 W/m·K). Max safe before substrate melting (1455°C) is ~300 W with short pulses. Source: IPG Photonics YLR series specs and study in Optics and Lasers in Engineering (2018) on metal surface cleaning.
Near-IR wavelength for efficient Nickel processing with good absorption
Optimal beam diameter for precision cleaning
High repetition rate for efficient cleaning coverage
Nanosecond pulse duration for effective contaminant ablation without substrate damage
Scanning speed for efficient area coverage
Number of cleaning passes for complete contaminant removal
Optimal overlap between adjacent scan lines for uniform cleaning
